  "_notes": {
    "vdp_classification": "Dönnhoff is a VDP member since 1991. The VDP hierarchy (Gutswein → Ortswein → Erste Lage → Grosse Lage) maps to wine-level classifications. Grosse Lage dry wines are labeled 'Grosses Gewächs' (GG). Grosse Lage sweet wines carry Prädikat designations (Kabinett, Spätlese, Auslese, BA, TBA, Eiswein).",
    "naming_convention": "German wine labels show: Village + Vineyard for Grosse Lage/Erste Lage wines (e.g., 'Niederhäuser Hermannshöhle'). Ortswein shows village name only (e.g., 'Schlossböckelheimer'). Gutswein shows no geographic designation.",
    "style_notes": "Dönnhoff produces both trocken (dry, <9 g/L RS) and fruchtig (fruity/off-dry to sweet) wines. GG wines are always dry. Kabinett wines are traditionally off-dry (~30-50 g/L RS). Spätlese fruity (~40-60 g/L RS). Auslese sweet. 'Goldkapsel' (gold capsule) indicates a special selection of higher ripeness within Auslese.",
    "wachenheimer_note": "The 2024 Wachenheimer Riesling Trocken is a one-off collaboration with Dr. Bürklin-Wolf (Pfalz) due to 2024 frost losses in the Nahe. Not a core portfolio wine.",
    "westhofener_note": "The 2024 Westhofener Riesling Trocken is from Rheinhessen (Westhofen village), not Nahe. Another frost-year collaboration.",
    "tonschiefer_note": "Tonschiefer ('clay slate') Riesling Trocken is sourced primarily from Oberhäuser Leistenberg (~80%) plus younger vines from Klamm and Hermannshöhle. It sits between Gutswein and Ortswein in the hierarchy — not officially classified but above estate level.",
    "s_wines_note": "The 'S' designation (Weissburgunder S, Grauburgunder S, Chardonnay S) indicates premium Burgundy varietal selections. Fermented dry, aged 6-9 months in new German oak Stückfässer (1,200L). The Doppelstück and Stückfass bottlings are entry-level Burgundy varietals.",
    "sparkling_note": "Dönnhoff produces traditional method Sekt: Pinot Brut (from Pinot Noir, 50+ months on lees, 11.5% ABV) and Riesling Brut Nature (zero dosage). Small production."
  },
